issue.title: feat: handlers for assign, deassign, extend and withdraw commands
issue.body:
# Task
Parse the incoming webhook event from an issue comment and perform one of the following:
1) **Assign** an issue to a contributor iff they are not currently assigned to another issue and the request is from a maintainer
2) **Deassign** a contributor from an issue if they are currently assigned and the request is from a maintainer
3) **Extend** time assigned to a contributor for an issue if the request is from a maintainer
4) **Withdraw** - if contributor assigned to an issue requests to withdraw

Each handler in turn makes calls to logic in #2 and #1 

# From Linear

pull_request.title: Test using a bit vector for storage instead of bytes
pull_request.body:
In the bitslice-based implementation, bits are stored in `[]byte`s, with each byte in the slice storing either a `0` or a `1`. Each bitslice is therefore taking up 7 times more space than necessary.

In this branch we try implementing a vector/slice of bits, where bits are still stored in `[]byte`s, but a byte holds 8 bits.

Preliminary results show that the bitslice-based implementation, while massively inefficient in its storage, is faster than the bit vector approach, by almost 2 orders of magnitude.

issue.title: feat: timer and pings for issue assignment, extension and inactivity tracking
issue.body:
# Task
Timer logic to track the following:
1) Approaching expiry of assignment deadline (ping the maintainer and contributor)
2) Expiry of issue assignment (ping the maintainer and contributor)
3) Extension of issue assignment (ping the maintainer and contributor)
4) Time since issue has been inactive i.e. no assignees (ping the maintainer and maintainer "unslacker")

**Note:** Separate issue but could be coupled with #1 

# Why?
Better tracking and accountability for a smoother experience

# From Linear

pull_request.title: feat(source): add new OffsetSource
pull_request.body:
Based on #228 so I could use the helpers in the examples, as the closures unfortunately can't detect the type they'll be called on.

I'm very open to suggestions on how to improve the usability here. I want the functionality for some personal projects where I gather configuration from various sources I don't control. Rather than trying to manipulate the data into the right format, it seems like it would be useful to have an option to load the data directly into the right place.

As per the examples provided, this can also be useful to load configuration that is _likely_ to be shared into multiple locations and then allow overriding them as needed.

commits.message:
feat: consolidate all infrastructure images into dedicated workflow (#241)

Infrastructure Workflow Consolidation:
- Create comprehensive infrastructure-build.yaml for all non-agent images
- Move PostgreSQL+pgvector image with high-dimensional vector support (3072-dim)
- Move rust-builder from separate runner-builld.yaml workflow
- Add runtime base image building with dependency management
- Consolidate PostgreSQL image from external repo into cto repo

Workflow Organization:
- agents-build.yaml: Pure AI agents (Claude, OpenHands, Gemini, etc.)
- infrastructure-build.yaml: Infrastructure (PostgreSQL, rust-builder, runtime)
- Proper separation of concerns and logical grouping
- Different schedules (agents at 6 AM, infrastructure at 7 AM)

New Features:
- Selective image building via workflow_dispatch (build specific images)
- Automatic runner cycling when rust-builder image updates
- Enhanced build summaries and GitHub Actions integration
- Support for both scheduled builds and manual triggers
- Fixed conditional logic to work properly with GitHub Actions matrix

Deprecation:
- Mark runner-builld.yaml as deprecated with clear migration path
- Direct users to new infrastructure workflow for rust-builder builds
- Maintain backward compatibility with deprecation notices

Benefits:
- Better workflow organization and separation of concerns
- Centralized infrastructure management in single repository
- Cleaner build triggers and dependency management
- Production-ready images with proper versioning and caching
